\cf1
{An important aspect of information distribution is the number of people involved
 in a project. As the number of people involved increases, the complexity of comm
unications increases because there are more communications channels or pathways t
hrough which people can communicate. There is a simple formula for determining th
e number of communications channels as the number of people involved in a project
 increases. You can calculate the number of communications channels as follows:\par
}\plain \f1
\fs22
\cf1
\pard
\widctlpar\keep\hyphpar0
\li0\ri0\fi0
\ql{\par
}\plain \f1
\fs22
\cf1
{\tab }\plain \f1
\fs22
\cf1
{number of communications channels = }\plain \i \f1
\fs22
\cf1
{n(n-1)/2}\plain \f1
\fs22
\cf1
{\par
}\plain \f1
\fs22
\cf1
{\par
}\plain \f1
\fs22
\cf1
{where }\plain \i \f1
\fs22
\cf1
{n }\plain \f1
\fs22
\cf1
{is the number of people involved.\par
}\plain \f1
\fs22
\cf1
{\par
}\plain \f1
\fs22
\cf1
{For example, two people have one communications channel: (2(2\'96
1))/2 = 1. Three p
eople have three channels: (3(3\'96
1))/2 = 3. Four people have six channels, five pe
ople have ten, and so on. As the number of people communicating increases above t
hree, the number of communications channels increases rapidly. Project managers s
hould try to limit the size of teams or sub teams to avoid making communications 
too complex.}\plain \f0
